WEBVTT

00:00:00.350 --> 00:00:06.264
As a super administrator, you can see the condition

00:00:06.264 --> 00:00:12.179
of multiple houses. Start with critical problems, missing backups,

00:00:12.179 --> 00:00:18.093
maintenance warnings and unusual audit events. Every entry must

00:00:18.093 --> 00:00:23.350
clearly identify the affected house before you act.

00:00:24.350 --> 00:00:31.497
The house selector changes the active administration context. The

00:00:31.497 --> 00:00:38.644
following views and actions refer to that house until

00:00:38.644 --> 00:00:45.791
you switch again. Check the house name and target

00:00:45.791 --> 00:00:51.350
especially before blocks, invitations or account changes.

00:00:52.350 --> 00:01:01.631
Super administrators can create houses with a clear name and address.

00:01:01.631 --> 00:01:10.913
Master data changes affect administration and display. Before deactivation, review active

00:01:10.913 --> 00:01:19.350
residents, bookings, resources, open workflows and the required data backup.

00:01:20.350 --> 00:01:27.100
A personal identity may be a resident of one house,

00:01:27.100 --> 00:01:33.850
a house administrator and additionally a super administrator. Resident bookings

00:01:33.850 --> 00:01:40.600
remain assigned to the apartment, while administrative actions are logged

00:01:40.600 --> 00:01:47.350
personally. Grant only the permissions required for the specific responsibility.

00:01:48.350 --> 00:01:55.769
A super administrator can grant an active house administrator additional super

00:01:55.769 --> 00:02:03.187
administrator rights. The existing super administrator keeps their rights, preventing an

00:02:03.187 --> 00:02:10.606
unintended sole handover. Revocation or planned succession requires password confirmation, an

00:02:10.606 --> 00:02:17.350
audit trail and at least one remaining capable super administrator.

00:02:18.350 --> 00:02:25.600
In the System area, check the time, integrity and destination

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:32.850
of database backups. A copy on the same server alone

00:02:32.850 --> 00:02:40.100
does not protect against a complete outage. Configure external storage

00:02:40.100 --> 00:02:47.350
and regularly verify that a backup can actually be restored.

00:02:48.350 --> 00:02:57.350
Use maintenance mode for major database or operational work. Inform residents,

00:02:57.350 --> 00:03:06.350
create a backup first and prevent new changes during the work.

00:03:06.350 --> 00:03:15.350
Afterwards, verify health status and core functions before restoring normal operation.

00:03:16.350 --> 00:03:23.273
The pilot reset is not a routine cleanup tool. Review

00:03:23.273 --> 00:03:30.196
exactly which bookings and test data will be removed, and

00:03:30.196 --> 00:03:37.119
create a backup immediately beforehand. Accounts, logbook evidence and production

00:03:37.119 --> 00:03:43.350
data must not accidentally become part of the reset.

00:03:44.350 --> 00:03:51.594
The audit records who performed an administrative action, when it happened

00:03:51.594 --> 00:03:58.838
and which house it affected. System status adds the version, database,

00:03:58.838 --> 00:04:06.082
email, push, backup and maintenance state. Investigate and document unusual events

00:04:06.082 --> 00:04:11.350
instead of silently removing them from the history.

00:04:12.350 --> 00:04:19.273
For role changes, house deactivation, maintenance and data resets, work

00:04:19.273 --> 00:04:26.196
deliberately. Verify the target, house, current backup, impact and recovery

00:04:26.196 --> 00:04:33.119
option. Confirm with your own current password, then review the

00:04:33.119 --> 00:04:39.350
audit and system status and document any remaining work.
